{"type":"message","id":"6a3cdca9","parentId":"efa9fcce","timestamp":"2026-02-11T19:27:30.150Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering File Navigation**\n\nI'm currently stuck with a huge output from `ls -R`. It's listing everything, including irrelevant `.venv` files. I'm pivoting to a simpler approach, using `ls` on the current directory without recursion. The goal is to isolate the application files for easier analysis. This should streamline the process.\n\n\n**Refining Directory Inspection**\n\nThe `ls` command, while useful, is proving to be a bit cumbersome. I'm thinking of incorporating a filter to the `ls` output. This should weed out those pesky hidden files and irrelevant directories. My aim is to extract the application files and core dependencies. This refined view will undoubtedly improve the accuracy of my analysis.\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"Команда `ls -R` выводит огромный и до сих пор не завершенный список. Похоже, она перечисляет абсолютно все файлы значков в каталоге `.venv`. Это бесполезно. Мне нужно найти основные файлы приложения.\n\nПопробую вывести список файлов и каталогов в текущем каталоге, но не рекурсивно, и, надеюсь, это даст мне лучшее представление о структуре проекта.","textSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1770838050142_30","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls"}}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-2.5-pro","usage":{"input":60468,"output":173,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":60641,"cost":{"input":0.075585,"output":0.0017300000000000002,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.077315}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1770838025900}}
